Armbruster states that the original location of the dwelling was at 49 Queens Boulevard.

folder: Queens Boulevard & Woodhaven Boulevard, Queens, NY
text:
Queens Boulevard, west side, between Woodhaven Boulevard and Eliot Avenue, showing three views of the Louis Bolsen house, still owned by him in 1924. It was erected on the site of the Gottlieb Reichert house which was destroyed by fire. Other owners of this property were H. Reickers, 1801; and Philip Reichert, 1891(?). Partially seen at the right foreground of view number three is the section of Mrs. Raymond's house which stood formerly at number 49 Queens Boulevard, opposite the Horan house. It is to be placed on the opposite side of the Boulevard near the hothouses in the foreground beyond the truck seen at the
left.
February 1924
Views 1 and 2
View 31: August 1924.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection

folder: Hoffman Drive & Woodhaven Boulevard, Queens, NY
text:
Hoffman Drive, west of Woodhaven Boulevard to 57th Road. This is a part of the old Road to Jamaica. The shed on the left fronts on the Robinson property. In the right foreground is the F. Plane house from 1873 to 1891. Adjoining this house is the Palmer house (1860-1891; not shown). The toll house stood just west of the last mentioned house.

March 1925.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

folder: Woodhaven Boulevard & Queens Boulevard, Queens, NY
text:
Woodhaven Boulevard, west side, just south of Queens Boulevard, showing an old house among fruit trees. It appears that a Mrs. Howard owned the property in 1873.

June 8, 1927

P. L. Sperr
